        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer70756616" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5942693235483804566">I’m beginning to understand why this series has such a large fan base!<br/><br/>The first book in this series certainly was promising but I found that a combination of Mercy’s dry tone narrative and a lack of action made it hard for me to get into the story. <br/>This time around I had a little trouble in the beginning, but soon after I got drawn into an engaging and exciting story in where the ever helpful Mercy gets sucked into vampire business (no pun intended). In the mean while, we learn more about Briggs</span>
  <span id="freeText5942693235483804566" style="display:none">I’m beginning to understand why this series has such a large fan base!<br /><br />The first book in this series certainly was promising but I found that a combination of Mercy’s dry tone narrative and a lack of action made it hard for me to get into the story. <br />This time around I had a little trouble in the beginning, but soon after I got drawn into an engaging and exciting story in where the ever helpful Mercy gets sucked into vampire business (no pun intended). In the mean while, we learn more about Briggs' world of vampires, Fae and werewolves. <br /><br />The world Briggs has built is absolutely fantastic and so real! And she does not glorify her supernatural characters. Her vampires are scary and unpredictable, the werewolves are bound by their hierarchic rules and old-fashioned prejudices and the Fae are not to be trusted. And still we feel for them, fear for them en get to love them.<br /><br />I’m really starting to love Mercy. I'm beginning to get the Mercy-Adam-Samuel triangle. But I must say: my favorite by far was Stefan! <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5942693235483804566" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
